==English==
===Etymology===
Old French ''[[aquest]]'', French ''[[acquêt]]'', from Late Latin ''[[acquestum]]'', ''[[acquisītum]]'', for Latin ''[[acquisītum]]'', past participle (used substantively) of ''[[acquirere]]'' to acquire. See [[acquire]]
===Noun===
#''(Rare):'' [[acquisition]]; the thing gained. [[w:Francis Bacon]].
#''(Law):'' property acquired by purchase, gift, or otherwise than by inheritance. - [[w:John Bouvier]].
#:'''NOTE:''' Bouvier, 1856, [http://www.constitution.org/bouv/bouvier_a.htm] from which the Webster derives, uses the spelling "acquets"

===Reference===
*Webster 1913

